\f2\fs22
\pard\qc\sb400\sa80\b\fs52\cf1 PVE Hunt Companion\b0\fs22\cf0\par
\pard\qc\sb60\sa80\fs28\cf3 Design Report — Hedge Ledger / DeFi Kingdoms\cf0\fs22\par
\pard\qc\sb40\sa600\fs22\cf3 March 2026\cf0\par
\pard\sb400\sa120\keepn\b\fs36\cf1 1. Design Intent\b0\fs22\cf0\par
\pard\li0\sb60\sa120 \fs22 The PVE Hunt Companion is a real-time tactical advisor designed to sit alongside a DeFi Kingdoms player during a PVE hunt battle. Its core purpose is to watch every turn unfold \u8212? parsing the live game UI \u8212? and surface the single best action the active hero should take, along with ranked alternatives, so that players make smarter combat decisions without needing deep knowledge of the underlying game math.\par
\pard\li0\sb60\sa120 \fs22 The system was designed around three guiding principles:\par
\pard\li360\fi-180\sb60\sa80 \fs22 \bullet  {\b Zero game modification: }The game client must not be altered. All data is extracted by observing the DOM, intercepting network calls, and reading rendered HTML \u8212? the game runs completely unchanged.\par
\pard\li360\fi-180\sb60\sa80 \fs22 \bullet  {\b Resilient delivery: }The Chrome Extension communicates with the Hedge Ledger backend over WebSocket when available, but gracefully degrades to an HTTP queue when the socket is down \u8212? ensuring no turn event is lost.\par
\pard\li360\fi-180\sb60\sa80 \fs22 \bullet  {\b Transparent reasoning: }Every recommendation is scored on a multi-dimensional weighted model (damage EV, kill chance, survival contribution, debuff utility, mana efficiency, initiative cost), and the reasons behind the top choice are shown to the player in plain language.\par
\pard\sb400\sa120\keepn\b\fs36\cf1 2. System Architecture\b0\fs22\cf0\par
\pard\li0\sb60\sa120 \fs22 The companion is a three-layer system: a Chrome Extension running inside the browser on the game page, a Node.js backend (Hedge Ledger) that stores events and runs the scoring engine, and a React admin dashboard that the operator watches in a separate window.\par
\pard\sb300\sa80\keepn\b\fs28\cf2 2.1 Chrome Extension\b0\fs22\cf0\par
\pard\li0\sb60\sa120 \fs22 The extension runs three distinct scripts simultaneously inside the browser:\par
\pard\li360\fi-180\sb60\sa80 \fs22 \bullet  {\b Content script (content.js): }Injected into game.defikingdoms.com. Detects the hunt/session ID from the URL, DOM attributes, page title, or SPA history hooks. Listens for battle log events, deduplicates them within a 500 ms window, and forwards them to the background worker. Also renders a fixed in-game overlay showing the current recommendation.\par
\pard\li360\fi-180\sb60\sa80 \fs22 \bullet  {\b Background service worker (background.js): }The central router. Maintains the WebSocket connection to /ws/companion with exponential-backoff reconnect (1s\u8594?30s). When the socket is available, events go out immediately. When it is down, events are pushed into an httpQueue that is persisted in chrome.storage.local and drained once connectivity returns. Also fetches hero profiles from the DFK GraphQL API or via the backend proxy.\par
\pard\li360\fi-180\sb60\sa80 \fs22 \bullet  {\b Popup (popup.html / popup.js): }Lets the operator paste their session token, see connection status, and check turn counter, queue depth, and current hunt ID.\par
\pard\sb300\sa80\keepn\b\fs28\cf2 2.2 Extension Sub-modules\b0\fs22\cf0\par
\pard\li0\sb60\sa120 \fs22 Parsers (read the game UI):\par
\pard\li360\fi-180 \bullet  \sb60\sa120 \fs22 parsers/battleLog.js \u8212? walks battle log DOM, emits events per visible action row.\par
\pard\li360\fi-180 \bullet  \sb60\sa120 \fs22 parsers/statPanel.js \u8212? reads stat panels for HP, MP, and status effects.\par
\pard\li360\fi-180 \bullet  \sb60\sa120 \fs22 parsers/turnState.js \u8212? captures active hero slot, legal actions, and HP/MP snapshot per combatant.\par
\pard\li0\sb60\sa120 \fs22 Interceptors (read the network when possible):\par
\pard\li360\fi-180 \bullet  \sb60\sa120 \fs22 interceptors/networkCapture.js \u8212? patches XHR and fetch to intercept DFK API calls and re-emit as DOM events.\par
\pard\li360\fi-180 \bullet  \sb60\sa120 \fs22 interceptors/networkNormalizer.js \u8212? converts raw DFK network payloads to the canonical event shape.\par
\pard\li0\sb60\sa120 \fs22 Local engine (in-browser scoring for offline / instant recommendations):\par
\pard\li360\fi-180 \bullet  \sb60\sa120 \fs22 engine/dataLoader.js, state.js, actions.js, heuristics.js, beam.js, normalizer.js, resolver.js \u8212? load game data, maintain live state, enumerate actions, run a heuristic pass and beam search, then resolve the final ranked recommendation.\par
\pard\sb300\sa80\keepn\b\fs28\cf2 2.3 Backend (bot.js \u8212? Node.js / Express)\b0\fs22\cf0\par
\pard\li0\sb60\sa120 \fs22 HTTP Endpoints: /api/dfk/telemetry/session (create session), /api/dfk/telemetry/event (HTTP-fallback turn events + scoring), /api/dfk/telemetry/snapshot (state snapshots + hero seeding), /api/dfk/reconcile (stat calibration), /api/admin/pve/companion/session (create token), /api/admin/pve/companion/session/:token (status + turn history), /api/admin/pve/companion/explain (AI explanation), /api/admin/pve/firebase-hunt-log (Firestore proxy), /api/dfk/hunt-heroes (server-side GraphQL hero lookup).\par
\pard\li0\sb60\sa120 \fs22 WebSocket Server (/ws/companion): Real-time bidirectional channel. Handles join (session validation, in-memory Map entry creation), state_snapshot (hero/enemy HP seeding), turn_event (persist + score + broadcast recommendation), request_hero_profiles, and battle_budget messages.\par
\pard\sb300\sa80\keepn\b\fs28\cf2 2.4 Admin Dashboard (React)\b0\fs22\cf0\par
\pard\li0\sb60\sa120 \fs22 hunt-companion.tsx opens a persistent WebSocket to /ws/companion and polls the session status endpoint every 3 seconds as a fallback. It shows the Hero Status strip (HP/MP bars), the Enemy bar, ranked Recommendations, a Turn Feed (last 10 events), and a collapsible Firebase Battle Log panel with HP bars and round/turn labels that auto-refreshes every 3 seconds while the battle is live.\par
\pard\sb400\sa120\keepn\b\fs36\cf1 3. How Data Is Fetched and Flows\b0\fs22\cf0\par
\pard\sb300\sa80\keepn\b\fs28\cf2 3.1 Turn Event Path\b0\fs22\cf0\par
\pard\li0\sb60\sa120 \fs22 WebSocket path (preferred):\par
\pard\li360\sb60\sa120\i\fs20\cf3 Game DOM / Network \u8594? content.js emits event \u8594? flushTurnEvent() \u8594? chrome.runtime.sendMessage(\{ type: "turn_event" \}) \u8594? background.js \u8594? sendOrQueue() \u8594? ws.send(JSON) \u8594? /ws/companion \u8594? scoring engine \u8594? ws.send(\{ type: "recommendation" \}) \u8594? dashboard.\i0\cf0\par
\pard\li0\sb60\sa120 \fs22 HTTP fallback path (when socket unavailable):\par
\pard\li360\sb60\sa120\i\fs20\cf3 background.js \u8594? httpQueue.push() \u8594? chrome.storage.local (persisted) \u8594? flushHttpQueue() \u8594? POST /api/dfk/telemetry/event \u8594? scoring engine \u8594? ws.send recommendation to dashboard WS clients.\i0\cf0\par
\pard\sb300\sa80\keepn\b\fs28\cf2 3.2 Hero Profile / State Snapshot Path\b0\fs22\cf0\par
\pard\li0\sb60\sa120 \fs22 On hunt detection, background.js calls the DFK GraphQL endpoint directly. If that fails, it falls back to GET /api/dfk/hunt-heroes on the backend. Profiles are cached in chrome.storage.local and broadcast to the content script. The WS path also supports request_hero_profiles which prompts a server-side GraphQL fetch and pushes profiles back. HP/MP state snapshots from turnState.js are sent each turn as state_snapshot messages, seeding the scoring engine's BattleState.\par
\pard\sb300\sa80\keepn\b\fs28\cf2 3.3 Firebase Battle Log Path\b0\fs22\cf0\par
\pard\li0\sb60\sa120 \fs22 The dashboard requests GET /api/admin/pve/firebase-hunt-log?huntRef=\{chainId\}-\{huntId\}. The server exchanges DFK_FIREBASE_REFRESH_TOKEN for a Google access token, calls DFK's Firestore REST API (combat-engine database), fetches battle-logs with pagination, and returns normalised combatant snapshots (heroes keyed "1", enemies keyed "-1") and turn summaries.\par
\pard\sb300\sa80\keepn\b\fs28\cf2 3.4 Scoring Engine Execution\b0\fs22\cf0\par
\pard\li0\sb60\sa120 \fs22 buildBattleStateFromTurnEvents() reconstructs the current BattleState from hero snapshots + turn history. scoreActions() then enumerates every legal action for the active hero (basic attack, affordable skills, consumables) and scores each on five weighted dimensions: damage EV (30%), kill chance (25%), survival delta (20%), debuff utility (10%), mana efficiency (8%), initiative (7%). The top five actions are returned as a Recommendation array and pushed to connected dashboard clients.\par
\pard\sb400\sa120\keepn\b\fs36\cf1 4. Where We Are Having Trouble\b0\fs22\cf0\par
\pard\sb300\sa80\keepn\b\fs28\cf2 4.1 Hero HP Seeding (\u8220?/ 135\u8221? Problem)\b0\fs22\cf0\par
\pard\li0\sb60\sa120 \fs22 The most persistent issue. When the extension's turnState.js parser runs before the HP bar has rendered, the state_snapshot contains hp:0 with maxHp:135 \u8212? making the scoring engine think all heroes are dead and producing meaningless recommendations. Mitigation: the seeding guard re-seeds whenever heroes is empty or every hero shows 0 currentHp with a positive maxHp. Root cause (game DOM timing) is not yet resolved.\par
\pard\sb300\sa80\keepn\b\fs28\cf2 4.2 Session Token Matching\b0\fs22\cf0\par
\pard\li0\sb60\sa120 \fs22 The operator must manually paste the session token from the dashboard into the extension popup. If they use a stale token, the WS join is rejected with "Invalid session token" and no in-memory session is created \u8212? meaning even HTTP-fallback events cannot run scoring. There is no auto-discovery or QR handshake mechanism yet.\par
\pard\sb300\sa80\keepn\b\fs28\cf2 4.3 HTTP-Fallback Scoring Requires Prior WS Join\b0\fs22\cf0\par
\pard\li0\sb60\sa120 \fs22 The companionSessions Map is populated only when a WS join message is received. If the extension never connects via WS (firewall, corporate proxy), then HTTP-fallback events arrive and companionSessions.get(token) returns null \u8212? the scoring engine silently skips. A fix would be to create the session Map entry on the first HTTP event, or have the dashboard send a lightweight HTTP register call. Not yet implemented.\par
\pard\sb300\sa80\keepn\b\fs28\cf2 4.4 Hunt ID Detection Reliability\b0\fs22\cf0\par
\pard\li0\sb60\sa120 \fs22 DFK is a React SPA. The hunt ID does not always appear in the URL \u8212? it can exist in app state only. The extension has four fallback strategies (URL pattern, DOM attributes/headings, page title, synthetic key from actor initials + timestamp), but none are perfect. When the synthetic key is generated, hero profile lookup fails because no real hunt ID is available, so scoring starts with no hero data.\par
\pard\sb300\sa80\keepn\b\fs28\cf2 4.5 Enemy Catalog Coverage\b0\fs22\cf0\par
\pard\li0\sb60\sa120 \fs22 pve-enemy-catalog.ts contains hand-coded entries for known PVE enemies. When the detected enemyId does not match any catalog entry, the engine cannot score at all. An ENEMY_ID_MAP normalises some aliases (e.g. "mad_boar" \u8594? "baby_boar"), but new enemy types added by game updates silently break scoring until the catalog is manually extended.\par
\pard\sb300\sa80\keepn\b\fs28\cf2 4.6 Firebase Side-Key Consistency\b0\fs22\cf0\par
\pard\li0\sb60\sa120 \fs22 Firestore battle documents use "1" for heroes and "-1" for enemies. Early development used "0" and "1", causing the companion panel to display units on the wrong side and label turns incorrectly. This was corrected in the latest revision. Any future consumer of the Firebase response must use the "1" / "-1" convention from hunt-battle-log.tsx as the canonical reference.\par
